T2  - JOURNAL OF ARCHITECTURAL AND PLANNING RESEARCH
AB  - American common law traditionally did not hold landlords civilly liable for criminal attack against their tenants and other business invitees. There is a trend, however, to find for plaintiffs where inadequate security measures have been taken, particularly if the risk of criminal attack is determined to have been reasonably foreseeable. Some premises liability cases have involved architects and engineering professionals where it has been argued that negligent design and/or site selection contributed to the likelihood crime would occur Principles of environmental criminology can be utilized to determine if there is actual notice that crime is reasonably foreseeable by looking at official and unofficial records. Constructive notice involves consideration of crime magnets, crime displacement, criminal mobility, population and vehicle traffic patterns, pedestrian traffic, and Crime Prevention Through Environmental Design.
